rnal=Gazette des Beaux-Arts|volume=72|pages=11\u2013144|ref=harv|oclc=888303109}}\n* {{cite book|last=Temperini|first=Renaud|year=2002|title=Watteau|series=Ma\u00eetres de l'art|language=fr|location=Paris|publisher=Gallimard|page=79|isbn=9782070116867|oclc=300225840|postscript=. Cat. no. 77.}}\n* {{cite magazine|last=Troubnikoff|first=A.|author-link=:ru:\u0422\u0440\u0443\u0431\u043d\u0438\u043a\u043e\u0432, \u0410\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0441\u0430\u043d\u0434\u0440 \u0410\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0441\u0430\u043d\u0434\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447|title=\u0424\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0446\u0443\u0437\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u0448\u043a\u043e\u043b\u0430 \u0432 \u0413\u0430\u0442\u0447\u0438\u043d\u0441\u043a\u043e\u043c \u0434\u0432\u043e\u0440\u0446\u0435 (La peinture fran\u00e7aise au ch\u00e2teau de Gatchina)|trans-title=\"French Painting in the Gatchina Palace\"|work=\u0421\u0442\u0430\u0440\u044b\u0435 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u044b|date=July\u2013September 1916|language=ru|pages=49\u201367}}\n* {{cite book|last=Zolotov|first=Y. K.|year=1968|title=\u0424\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0446\u0443\u0437\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u043f\u043e\u0440\u0442\u0440\u0435\u0442 XVIII \u0432\u0435\u043a\u0430|trans-title=French Portrait in the Eighteenth Century|location=Moscow|publisher=Iskusstvo|pages=28, 30|oclc=567935709}}\n* {{cite book|editor-last=Zolotov|editor-first=Y. K.|title=\u0410\u043d\u0442\u0443\u0430\u043d \u0412\u0430\u0442\u0442\u043e (\u0430\u043b\u044c\u0431\u043e\u043c \u0440\u0435\u043f\u0440\u043e\u0434\u0443\u043a\u0446\u0438\u0439)|trans-title=Antoine Watteau: a reproductions album|language=ru|year=1973|ref=harv|location=Leningrad|publisher=Aurora|pages=138\u2013140|oclc=46947007}}\n{{refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{cite web|url=http://watteau-abecedario.org/Coquettes_qui_pour_voir.htm|title=Coquettes qui pour voir|last=Eidelberg|first=Martin|author-link=Martin Eidelberg|date=January 2019|work=A Watteau Abecedario|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190403191650/http://watteau-abecedario.org/Coquettes_qui_pour_voir.htm|archive-date=April 3, 2019|accessdate=April 11, 2019|ref=harv}}\n* [http://www.hermitagemuseum.org/wps/portal/hermitage/digital-collection/01.%20paintings/37439?lng=en ''Actors of the Com\u00e9die-Fran\u00e7aise''] at the Hermitage's official website\n\n{{Jean-Antoine Watteau}}\n\n[[Category:Oil paintings]]\n[[Category:Panel painting]]\n[[Category:1710s paintings]]\n[[Category:Paintings by Antoine Watteau]]\n[[Category:Paintings of the Hermitage Museum]]\n[[Category:Paintings of children]]\n[[Category:Portraits of actors|Comedie-Francaise]]\n[[Category:18th-century portraits]]\n[[Category:Group portraits]]\n[[Category:Crozat collection]]\n", "text_old": "<noinclude>{{User:RMCD bot/subject notice|1=Coquettes qui pour voir|2=Talk:Actors of the Com\u00e9die-Fran\u00e7aise#Requested move 8 April 2020 }}\n</noinclude>{{italic title}}\n{{Expand French|Les Acteurs de la Com\u00e9die-Fran\u00e7aise|date=July 2018}}\n{{Infobox artwork\n| image_file = File:Antoine_Watteau_062.jpg\n| title = Coquettes qui pour voir \n| other_title_1 = Actors of the Com\u00e9die-Fran\u00e7aise\n| image_size = 240px\n| artist = [[Jean-Antoine Watteau]]\n| year = Between 1711\u20131717\n| material = [[panel painting|oil on panel]]\n| height_metric = 20\n| width_metric = 25\n| city = [[Saint Petersburg]]\n| museum = [[Hermitage Museum|The Hermitage]]\n| accession = \u0413\u042d-1131\n}}\n'''''Coquettes qui pour voir''''' is the name commonly given to an [[Panel painting|oil on panel]] painting in the [[Hermitage Museum]] in [[Saint Petersburg]], by French artist [[Jean-Antoine Watteau]], the leading painter of the [[R\u00e9gence]] era and a pioneer of the [[Rococo]] style. Completed in the 1710s, it forms a half-length group portrait, possibly the rarest case in Watteau's body of work, and has been given various interpretatons; some scholars believe it to be a depiction of [[commedia dell'arte masks]], while some others believe it to be a depiction of members of the [[Com\u00e9die-Fran\u00e7aise]]. Because of that, the painting has been known under a number of various titles; its traditional naming in Western scholarship, ''Coquettes qui pour voir'', is derived from anonymous verses which the painting was featured with in [[Jean de Jullienne]]'s [[Recueil Jullienne|four-volume collection]] of engravings after Watteau's works.  \n\nBy the middle of the 18th century, ''Coquettes'' belonged to {{ill|Louis-Antoine Crozat, Baron de Thiers|fr|Louis Antoine Crozat}}, a nephew of the Parisian merchant and art collector [[Pierre Crozat]]; after his death in 1770, the painting, along with a most part of the collection he owned, was acquired for [[Catherine II of Russia]] in 1772. Since then the painting was held among the Russian imperial family collections in the Hermitage and, after the 1850s, in the [[Gatchina Palace]]; in 1920, it was transitioned in the Winter Palace, where it currently remains as part of the Hermitage Museum permanent exhibition. In Russian literature, the painting is currently known as '''''Actors of the Com\u00e9die-Fran\u00e7aise'''''{{efn|{{lang-ru|\u00ab\u0410\u043a\u0442\u0451\u0440\u044b \u0444\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0446\u0443\u0437\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0442\u0435\u0430\u0442\u0440\u0430\u00bb}}; adopted into French as ''Acteurs de la Com\u00e9die-Fran\u00e7aise''<ref name=bordeaux1980/> or ''Les comediens fran\u00e7ais''.{{sfn|Zolotov|1985|p=98}}}}, following studies of Watteau's drawings that established a possible identity.\n\n==Description==\n===Composition===\n{{quote box|align=left|width=25%|quote=\"\u2026Watteau combines portraiture with a striking feeling for the picturesque. The rounded, resilient brushstrokes seem to have benn applied with the lightness of spontaneous improvisation, yet at the same time with a bold precision which only a mature master could command. The faces, showing fatigue, animation and faint anxiety, are illuminated by a mysterious theatrical light, the fantastic costumes shimmer with wine-pink tones against the black velvet of the masks. All this creates an impression of the natural unity of the imagined and the actual, a [[E. T. A. Hoffmann|Hoffmannesque]] world where the characters\u2019 reality in only enhanced by the strangeness of their surroundings.\"|source=\u2014[[Mikhail German]] on ''Actors...'', in a 1980 artbook ''Antoine Watteau''.{{sfn|German|1980|p=8}}}}\n''Actors ...'' is an oil on panel painting upholstered in wood, and measures approximately 20 \u00d7 25&nbsp;cm.{{sfnm|Nemilova|1964|1p=181|2a1=Grasselli|2a2=Rosenberg|2a3=Parmantier|2y=1984|2p=311}}\n\nIn the painting, Watteau depicts five figures in half-length, standing around a stone balustrade. To the right, an outwardly old man stands upon a stick and holds a mushroom hat, dressed in a skullcap. By the balustrade's other side, a young girl is shown in a light-colored striped dress with high standing collar, standing behind a black boy in green-striped clothes. Over the girl's shoulder, a man's head appears in a large motley beret. To the left side, a young woman turned to the right in profile, appears in a Polish-styled red dress and white chipper, leaning on the balustrade and holding a black mask in the right hand.{{sfn|Nemilova|1964|p=181}}\n\nDefects found on the panel include a restored crack to the right of the old man's cape; gaps in shadows, more importantly at the bottom edge and around the girl's head; chippings painted over the girl's left shoulder.{{sfn|Nemilova|1964|p=181}} An X-ray analysis published by Soviet scholars in 1973 revealed changes in the composition showing that in the early stages the woman at the left was bareheaded, wore a different costume, and had placed her mask on the balustrade. The several differences between the painting and the engraving, notably in the coiffure of the central female figure, are considered relating to the state of the painting, which has been somewhat damaged and restored in the past.{{sfnm|Zolotov|1973|1p=138|Nemilova|1982|2pp=130\u2013131|3a1=Grasselli|3a2=Rosenberg|3a3=Parmantier|3y=1984|3p=312}}\n\n<!--[[Donald Posner]] described ''Actors'' less successful in its idea and composition, while having beautiful painting of individual forms.{{sfn|Posner|1984|p=290}}-->\n\n===Identity of subjects===\n[[File:Henri Simon Thomassin - Coquettes qui pour voir galans au rendez-vous.jpg|thumb|The painting's traditional naming originates from {{Interlanguage link|Henri Simon Thomassin|lt=Henri Simon Thomassin's|fr}} engraving, executed for the ''Recueil Jullienne''.]]\nUntil the middle of the 20th century, sources and studies on Watteau variously defined the work's subject. In notes to [[Pellegrino Antonio Orlandi]]'s ''Abecedario pittorico'', [[Pierre-Jean Mariette]] referred to the work as ''Coquettes qui pour voir galans au rendez vous'' ({{trans|\"Coquettish women, who to meet gallant men go around...\"}}), after the first verses of quatrains accompanying Thomassin's engraving for the ''Recueil Jullienne''; Mariette thought the panel depicts \"people in disguise for a ball, among whom is one dressed as an old man.\"<ref name=\"Dacier & Co\">{{cite book|first=\u00c9mile|last=Dacier|first2=Albert|last2=Vuaflart|title=Jean de Julienne et les graveurs de Watteau au XVIII-e si\u00e8cle. III. Catalogue|date=1922|location=Paris|language=fr|publisher=M. Rousseau|page=23}}</ref> [[Fran\u00e7ois-Bernard L\u00e9pici\u00e9]] refers to the composition as ''Retour de Bal'' in a 1741 obituary of {{Interlanguage link|Henri Simon Thomassin|fr}}, believing the figures to be returning from a ball;<ref>{{Cite magazine|last=L\u00e9pici\u00e9|first=F. B.|date=March 1741|title=Lettre sur la mort de M. Thomassin|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CZJQAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA568#v=onepage&q&f=false|journal=Mercure de France|pages=568\u2013570|via=[[Google Books]]|language=fr}}</ref>{{rp|569}}{{sfn|Camesasca|1971|p=115|loc=cat. no. 162}} in contrary, ''Catalogue Crozat'' of 1755 and [[Dezallier d'Argenville#Antoine-Nicolas Dezallier d'Argenville|Dezallier d'Argenville ''fils'']] described it as a depiction of masked figures preparing for a ball.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Catalogue des tableaux du cabinet de M. Crozat Baron de Thi\u00e8res \u00e1 Paris|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=L9DJyvbqgKcC&pg=PA65|year=1755|language=fr|location=Paris|page=65|via=Google Books}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Voyage Pictoresque de Paris|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6aZfAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA140#v=onepage&q&f=false|last=Dezallier d'Argenville|first=Antoine-Nicolas|year=1757|location=Paris|page=140|orig-year=1749|language=fr|via=Google Books|quote=Des personnages en masque se pr\u00e9parant pour le bal, par Watteau. Il y en a une estampe grav\u00e9e par Thomassin.}}</ref>\n\nLater sources, more prominently in France and Russia, similarly had various definitions on the subject: {{Interlanguage link|Johann Ernst von Munnich|ru|\u041c\u0438\u043d\u0438\u0445, \u0418\u043e\u0433\u0430\u043d\u043d \u042d\u0440\u043d\u0441\u0442}} refers to the work as ''Personnages en masques'' ({{trans|\"Characters in Masks\"}}) in the two-volume catalogue of the Hermitage collection;<ref>{{Cite book|title=Catalogue raisonn\u00e9 des tableaux qui trouvent dans les Galeries et Cabinets du Palais Imp\u00e9rial \u00e0 Saint-P\u00e9tersbourg|last=Munnich|first=Johann Ersnt von|date=1773\u20131783|volume=1|page=274|language=fr|postscript=. Cat. no. 873.}}</ref> the Hermitage's 1797 catalogue features the title ''The Mascarade'',<ref>{{cite book|title=\u041a\u0430\u0442\u0430\u043b\u043e\u0433 \u043a\u0430\u0440\u0442\u0438\u043d\u0430\u043c, \u0445\u0440\u0430\u043d\u044f\u0449\u0438\u043c\u0441\u044f \u0432 \u0418\u043c\u043f\u0435\u0440\u0430\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u0413\u0430\u043b\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0435 \u042d\u0440\u043c\u0438\u0442\u0430\u0436\u0430|editor-last=Labensky|editor-first=F. I.|trans-title=Catalogue of Paintings housed in the Imperial Hermitage Gallery|year=1797|language=ru|volume=2|page=55|postscript=. Cat. no. 2545.}}</ref> whereas the 1859 inventory registry features only the work's description\u2014\"two women, talking with two men, and a negro beside them\".<ref>{{cite book|title=\u041e\u043f\u0438\u0441\u044c \u043a\u0430\u0440\u0442\u0438\u043d\u0430\u043c \u0438 \u043f\u043b\u0430\u0444\u043e\u043d\u0430\u043c, \u0441\u043e\u0441\u0442\u043e\u044f\u0449\u0438\u043c \u0432 \u0437\u0430\u0432\u0435\u0434\u044b\u0432\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0438 II \u043e\u0442\u0434\u0435\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f \u0418\u043c\u043f\u0435\u0440\u0430\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u042d\u0440\u043c\u0438\u0442\u0430\u0436\u0430|trans-title=Inventory of paintings and plafonds in the office of the Second Department of the Imperial Hermitage Museum|language=ru|year=1859|postscript=. Cat. no. 1699}}</ref>{{sfnm|Nemilova|1964|1pp=81, 181|Nemilova|1970|2pp=145\u2013146|Nemilova|1989|3p=133}} In his writings, {{Interlanguage link|Pierre Edmond Alexandre H\u00e9douin|lt=Edmond H\u00e9douin|fr|Pierre Edmond Alexandre H\u00e9douin}} referred the work to as ''Le Rendez-vous du bal masqu\u00e9'',{{sfn|Hedouin|1856|loc=cat. no. 30|p=97}} before [[Edmond de Goncourt]]'s ''Catalogue raisonn\u00e9...'' introduced the Mariette-mentioned title into common use.{{sfnm|1a1=Grasselli|1a2=Rosenberg|1a3=Parmantier|1y=1984|1pp=312\u2013313|Eidelberg|2019|2ps=: \"Beginning with Edmond de Goncourt, it has become customary to assign the painting the awkward name of ''Coquettes qui pour voir'', the opening words of the two quatrains that appears under the Thomassin engraving.\"}}\n\nIn an 1896 article published in ''[[Gazette des Beaux-Arts]]'', Gaston Sch\u00e9fer presumed that ''Coquettes'' is probably composed out of portrait sketches and that the lady in red is the French actress [[Charlotte Desmares]],{{efn|[[Charlotte Desmares|Christine Antoinette Charlotte Desmares]] (1682\u20131753) performed in the [[Com\u00e9die-Fran\u00e7aise]] from 1690 to 1721; at some point, she was a mistress of [[Philippe II, Duke of Orl\u00e9ans]]. According to Fran\u00e7ois Moureau's article \"Watteau in His Time\" published in the ''Watteau, 1684\u20131721'' exhibition catalogue, Desmares \"had numerous reasons for meeting Watteau.\"{{sfn|Grasselli|Rosenberg|Parmantier|1984|p=477}}. Nemilova presumed that Watteau was introduced to Desmares by his friend, ''[[Mercure de France]]'' editor [[Antoine de Laroque]].{{sfnm|Nemilova|1970|1p=156|Nemilova|1989|2p=152}}}} based on comparison of the composition with Lepici\u00e9's engraving of her portrait by [[Charles-Antoine Coypel]];{{sfn|Sch\u00e9fer|1896|pp=185\u2013186|postscript=: \"Ce tableau des ''Coquettes'' n'est probablement fait que de portraits, de ces t\u00eates d'etudes que Watteau crayonnait sur ses cahiers. Quels portraits? nous l'ignorons. Tout au plus hasarderons-nous quelque supposition vraisemblable sur cette jeune femme au nez retrouss\u00e9, aux joues rebondies, que l'on voit \u00e0 droit, coiff\u00e9e d'un grand bonnet oriental et qui rappelle Mlle Desmares, de la Com\u00e9die Fran\u00e7aise. Assur\u00e9ment, ce n'est pas la P\u00e8lerine dont Watteau a trac\u00e9 la fr\u00eate silhouette dans les \"Figures de Mode\"; cette figurine est si menue que l'on a peine \u00e0 distinguer sa physionomie. Mais le grande portrait de Lepici\u00e9 nous donne assez exactement le visage et les formes abondantes de la com\u00e9dienne pour que notre hypoth\u00e8se soit autoris\u00e9e.\"}} Later in the early 1900s, French author Virgile Josz presumed the painting to be a depiction of [[commedia dell'arte masks]], with the old man as [[Pantalone]], the women as Rosaura and [[Isabella (commedia dell'arte)|Isabella]], and the young man as [[Scapino]];{{sfnm|Josz|1903|1pp=329\u2013330|Josz|1904|2p=146}} in later years, these points were adopted by a number of scholars{{efn|Virgile Josh\u2019s description of ''Coquettes...'' had been adopted by a number of scholars, including the Russians [[Alexandre Benois]],<ref name=\"Benois 1908\">{{cite magazine|last=Benois|first=Alexandre|author-link=Alexandre Benois|title=\u0416\u0438\u0432\u043e\u043f\u0438\u0441\u044c \u044d\u043f\u043e\u0445\u0438 \u0431\u0430\u0440\u043e\u043a\u043a\u043e \u0438 \u0440\u043e\u043a\u043e\u043a\u043e|language=ru|trans-title=Painting in the Age of Baroque and Rococo|department=1908: \u0412\u044b\u0441\u0442\u0430\u0432\u043a\u0430 \u043a\u0430\u0440\u0442\u0438\u043d|work=\u0421\u0442\u0430\u0440\u044b\u0435 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u044b|pages=720\u2013734|date=November\u2013December 1908}}</ref>{{rp|729}}<ref name=\"Benois 1910\">{{cite book|last=Benois|first=Alexandre|editor-last=Weiner|editor-first=P. P.|editor-link=:ru:\u0412\u0435\u0439\u043d\u0435\u0440, \u041f\u0451\u0442\u0440 \u041f\u0435\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447|date=1910|chapter=La Peinture Fran\u00e7aise, Italienne et Anglaise aux xviie et xviiie si\u00e8cles|chapter-url=https://archive.org/details/lesanciennesco00bruxuoft/page/n256|title=Les Anciennes \u00e9coles de peinture dans les palais et collections priv\u00e9es russes, repr\u00e9sent\u00e9es \u00e0 l'exposition organis\u00e9e \u00e0 St.- P\u00e9tersbourg en 1909 par la revue d'art ancien \"Stary\u00e9 gody\"|url=https://archive.org/details/lesanciennesco00bruxuoft|location=Bruxelles|publisher=G. van Oest|pages=105\u2013119|via=the Internet Archive|quote=D'un tout autre genre est un petit tableau de Watteau connu dans la gravure sous le nom \u00abLes Coquettes\u00bb. Le coloris n'en est pas recherch\u00e9, mais les characters d'Isabelle la rus\u00e9e, du stupide Pantalon, de la gaie Rosaure et du fourbe Scapin sont rendus avec amour et une grande finessee.}}</ref> Valentin Miller,<ref name=\u201cgorod1923\u201d>{{cite book|last=Miller|first=V.|chapter=\u0424\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0446\u0443\u0437\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u0436\u0438\u0432\u043e\u043f\u0438\u0441\u044c XVII-\u0433\u043e \u0438 XVIII-\u0433\u043e \u0432.\u0432. \u0432 \u043d\u043e\u0432\u044b\u0445 \u0437\u0430\u043b\u0430\u0445 \u042d\u0440\u043c\u0438\u0442\u0430\u0436\u0430 (L\u2019art fran\u00e7ais du XVIII-i\u00e8me et du XVIII-i\u00e8me s.s. dans les nouvelles salles de l\u2019Ermitage)|trans-chapter=\u201cFrench Painting of the Seventeenth and Eighteenth Centuries in the New Rooms of the Hermitage\u201d|title=\u0413\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0434: \u043b\u0438\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0430\u0442\u0443\u0440\u0430, \u0438\u0441\u043a\u0443\u0441\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e|location=\u041f\u0435\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0431\u0443\u0440\u0433|publisher=\u0413\u0440\u0430\u0444\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0435 \u043c\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0435 \u0410\u043a\u0430\u0434\u0435\u043c\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0438\u0437\u0434\u0430\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0430|year=1923|pages=52\u201378|oclc=32361994}}</ref>{{rp|58\u201359}} and {{Interlanguage link|Sergei Ersnt|ru|\u042d\u0440\u043d\u0441\u0442, \u0421\u0435\u0440\u0433\u0435\u0439 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0438\u0441\u043b\u0430\u0432\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447}},<ref name=Ersnt>{{Cite magazine|last=Ernst|first=Serge|author-link=Sergei Ernst|date=March 1928|title=L\u2019exposition de peinture fran\u00e7aise des XVIIe et XVIIIe siecles au mus\u00e9e de l\u2019Ermitage, a Petrograd (1922\u20131925)|url=https://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k61112882/f191.image.r=watteau|magazine=[[Gazette des Beaux-Arts]]|volume=17|issue=785|language=fr|pages=163\u2013182|access-date=March 29, 2019|via=[[Gallica]]}}</ref>{{rp|172\u2013173}} as well as the Hermitage Museum's 1958 catalogue of the painting collection.<ref>{{Cite book|title=\u0413\u043e\u0441\u0443\u0434\u0430\u0440\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u042d\u0440\u043c\u0438\u0442\u0430\u0436. \u041e\u0442\u0434\u0435\u043b \u0437\u0430\u043f\u0430\u0434\u043d\u043e\u0435\u0432\u0440\u043e\u043f\u0435\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0438\u0441\u043a\u0443\u0441\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0430: \u041a\u0430\u0442\u0430\u043b\u043e\u0433 \u0436\u0438\u0432\u043e\u043f\u0438\u0441\u0438|publisher=Iskusstvo|year=1958|editor-last=Levinson-Lessing|editor-first=V. F.|volume=1|location=Leningrad, Moscow|page=270|language=ru|trans-title=The State Hermitage Museum. The Department for Western European Art: Catalog of Paintings}}</ref>}} Josz's contemporary {{Interlanguage link|Louis de Fourcaud|fr}} considered figures to be \"a family group dressed for an elegant masquerade,\" painted after material from sketchbooks.<ref name=\"Fourcaud\">{{cite magazine|first=Louis de|last=Fourcaud|title=Antoine Watteau: scenes et figures th\u00e9atrales (I)|url=https://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k4325209/f150.image|language=fr|work=La Revue de l'art ancien et moderne|date=February 1904|volume=15|issue=83|pages=135\u2013150|access-date=March 31, 2019|via=Gallica}}</ref>{{rp|144}}{{sfnm|Nemilova|1964|1pp=81, 181|Nemilova|1970|2pp=145\u2013147|3a1=Grasselli|3a2=Rosenberg|3a3=Parmantier|3y=1984|3p=312|Nemilova|1989|4p=133}}\n\nIn her monograph on Watteau published in 1950, Helene Adhemar identified the lady in red as [[Charlotte Desmares]], similarly to Sch\u00e9fer; Adhemar's point was furthered in [[Karl Parker]] and Jacques Mathey's 1957\u20131958 catalogue of Watteau drawings; they concluded that the old man could be another Com\u00e9die-Fran\u00e7aise player, Pierre Le Noir.{{efn|Pierre Le Noir (1657\u20131731) was a son of [[La Thorilli\u00e8re|Fran\u00e7ois Le Noir ''dit'' La Thorilli\u00e8re]], a prominent actor associated with [[Moli\u00e8re]]\u2019s [[Moli\u00e8re's company|company]]. He joined the royal troupe in 1671, first as a touring artist; in 1684, Le Noir became a ''[[Soci\u00e9taires of the Com\u00e9die-Fran\u00e7aise|soci\u00e9taire]]'' of the Com\u00e9die-Fran\u00e7aise. Le Noir, also known as La Thorilli\u00e8re like his father was, mostly performed ''a manteau'' roles.{{sfnm|1a1=Grasselli|1a2=Rosenberg|1a3=Parmantier|1y=1984|1p=478|Nemilova|1989|2p=140}}}} In the Soviet Union, the Hermitage staff member Inna Nemilova supported these points, and also concluded the young man to be [[Philippe Poisson (actor)|Philippe Poisson]].{{sfn|Belova|2006|pp=58\u201359}}{{sfnm|Zolotov|1973|1p=139|Nemilova|1982|2pp=131\u2013133|Nemilova|1989|3pp=137\u2013138, 140, 142, 144, 146}} In addition, Nemilova pointed out Desmares could be possibly depicted by Watteau in both versions of ''[[The Embarkation for Cythera]]'', and also other canvas{{efn|These include ''The Island of Cythera'' (''The Embarkation''\u2019s preceding work, now in the [[St\u00e4del Museum]] in Frankfurt), ''The Dreamer'' (now in the [[Art Institute of Chicago]]), ''The Polish Woman'' (now in the [[National Museum, Warsaw|National Museum in Warsaw]]), and the lost ''La Polonnoise'' engraved by {{Interlanguage link|Michel Aubert|lt=Michel Aubert|fr}}.}} and various drawings.{{sfn|Nemilova|1964|pp=86\u201387, 91}}\n<!--In a 1980 biography of Watteau, Mikhail German was sceptical of Nemilova's point; he said he \"would like to believe this lady is really the actress Christine Desmares,\" and is not \"going to insist the man to the right is really [...] La Thorilli\u00e8re.\"{{sfn|German|2010|loc=chapter X|p=105}}-->\n\n===Authorship and dating===\nWatteau's authorship of the panel has never been seriously questioned by scholars until the early 20th century, when {{Interlanguage link|Nicolas Wrangel (art historian)|lt=Nicolas Wrangel|ru|\u0412\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0433\u0435\u043b\u044c, \u041d\u0438\u043a\u043e\u043b\u0430\u0439 \u041d\u0438\u043a\u043e\u043b\u0430\u0435\u0432\u0438\u0447}} considered it a work by [[Philippe Mercier]] in a 1912 letter to his German colleague Ernst Heinrich Zimmermann; the latter chose to classify it among the \"doubtful pictures;\"<ref>{{Cite book|title=Watteau: des Meisters Werke in 182 Abbildungen|last=Zimmermann|first=E. Heinrich|publisher=Deutsche Verlags-Anstalt|year=1912|location=Stuttgart, Leipzig|pages=190\u2013191|language=de|author-link=:de:Ernst Heinrich Zimmermann|series=Klassiker der Kunst|volume=21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite magazine|last=Ettinger|first=P. D.|date=1912|title=Rossica|language=ru|magazine=[[Apollon (magazine)|Apollon]]|issue=7|pages=61\u201362|postscript=. [http://www.v-ivanov.it/apollon/apollon_1912_07.pdf See] a facsimile copy at the Vyacheslav Ivanov Research Center archive.}}</ref> similarly, [[Jean Ferr\u00e9]] included the work among \"attributed to Watteau.\"<ref>{{Cite book|title=Watteau|editor-last=Ferr\u00e9|editor-first=Jean|editor-link=Jean Ferr\u00e9|publisher=\u00c9ditions Athena|year=1972|volume=1|location=Madrid|pages=151\u2013152}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Watteau|editor-last=Ferr\u00e9|editor-first=Jean|editor-link=Jean Ferr\u00e9|publisher=\u00c9ditions Athena|year=1972|volume=3|location=Madrid|page=966}}</ref> Later studies have ruled possible doubts out, given the work's high artistic qualities as well as preparatory drawings and Thomassin's engraving; in her 1964 monograph, Nemilvova presumed Wrangel have been led to his conclusion because of the work's presence in the Gatchina Palace;{{sfnm|Nemilova|1964|1pp=28\u201329, 181|Nemilova|1982|2p=133|3a1=Grasselli|3a2=Rosenberg|3a3=Parmantier|3y=1984|3pp=311\u2013312}} in an entry for ''A Watteau Abecedario'', [[Martin Eidelberg]] adds that Mercier could not paint with the same characteristics and artistic level Watteau had, but also reveals that Wrangel pointed out supposed differences between the Hermitage painting and Thomassin\u2019s engraving: the blond actress lacks the coiffure seen in the engraving, there are also differences in the actor at the right.{{sfn|Eidelberg|2019}}\n\nScholars were also divided over the dating of ''Actors \u2026''. Adhemar presumed the work has been completed within a period from Spring to Autumn of 1716.{{sfn|Adhemar|1950|loc=cat. no. 154|p=119}} Similarly, [[Charles Sterling]]{{sfn|Sterling|1958|p=41}} had suggested a 1716\u20131717 dating, whereas Donald Posner{{sfn|Posner|1984|p=290}} opted for a 1717 dating, and so did Giovanni Macchia and Ettore Montagni;{{efn|Co-authors of a 1968 catalogue of Watteau's work from the ''L'opera competa di...'' series, edited by {{Interlanguage link|Ettore Camesasca|pt}}; later editions in French and English, published in the early 1970's, have the catalogue's authorship credited to Camesasca.}}{{sfn|Camesasca|1971|loc=cat. no. 162|p=115}} in 1959, Mathey proposed a relatively early date of 1714.<ref name=\"Mathey 1959, p. 68\">{{cite book|last=Mathey|first=Jacques|title=Antoine Watteau. Peintures r\u00e9apparues inconnues ou n\u00e9glig\u00e9es par les historiens|location=Paris|publisher=F. de Nobele|year=1959|language=fr|page=68}}</ref> Regarding aforementioned datings as too late, Nemilova dated ''Actors \u2026'' within a period of 1711\u20131712,{{efn|Claims of Nemilova's other or changed datings, most notably by Macchia and Montagni (see {{harvnb|Camesasca|1971|loc=cat. no. 162|p=115}}), are considered erroneous.{{sfnm|Nemilova|1985|1p=445|Zolotov|1985|2p=100}}}} based on similarities with another Watteau composition, ''Du bel \u00e2ge\u2026'',{{efn|''Du bel \u00e2ge\u2026'' is a lost painting, believed by Montagni ({{harvnb|Camesasca|1971|p=100}}) and {{harvtxt|Posner|1984|p=290}} to be a pendant to ''Les entretiens badins...'', also lost. These both were engraved separately by Jean Moyreau and [[Beno\u00eet Audran the Younger]], respectively, and were published in the ''Recueil Jullienne'', appearing on the same page. In 1850, they have appeared on the market at the Caissotti sale; since then, their whereabouts are unknown. Adhemar and Posner dated ''Du bel \u00e2ge\u2026'' ca. 1712, while {{harvtxt|Mathey|1959|p=66}} used a dating not earlier than 1704\u20131705; Montagni used a 1710 dating.{{sfn|Camesasca|1971|p=100|loc=cat. no. 58|ps=; illustration on p. 98.}}}} as it has characters depicted in half-length with compositional rhythm and visual features similar to these on ''Coquettes...''.{{sfnm|Nemilova|1964|1p=182|Nemilova|1970|2p=156|Nemilova|1985|3p=445}} Others authors, such as [[Pierre Rosenberg]],{{sfn|Grasselli|Rosenberg|Parmantier|1984|p=312}} Marianne Roland Michel,{{sfn|Roland Michel|1984|p=217}} and Mary Vidal,<ref>\n{{Cite book|title=Watteau's Painted Conversations: Art, Literature, and Talk in Seventeenth- and Eighteenth-Century France|last=Vidal|first=Mary|publisher=Yale University Press|year=1992|isbn=0-300-05480-7|location=New Haven, London|page=146|postscript=. Ill. 142}}</ref> proposed a 1714-1715 dating; Roland Michel, while accepting identities suggested by Nemilova, objected her dating as too early and not taking into account the psychological study of subjects.{{sfn|Roland Michel|1984|p=217}}\n<!--\n==Provenance==\nIn an article published in the March 1928 issue of ''[[Gazette des Beaux-Arts]]'', Ernst reported that In years following Watteau's death, ''Actors...'' were owned by the royal collections conservator Nicolas Bailly, from which it passed to Pierre Crozat and his successors before 1755.{{rp|172\u2013173}} In 1772, it was acquired by [[Catherine II of Russia]], and was placed in the [[Winter Palace]]. At some point after the 1850s, it was relocated into the [[Gatchina Palace]]. In 1920, it was transitioned into the Winter Palace again, becoming an exhibit of the Hermitage's expositions.{{sfn|Nemilova|1964|pp=28-29, 182}}\n-->\n\n== Exhibition history ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ List of major exhibitions featuring the work\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Year\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Title\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Location\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Cat. no.\n! colspan=\"2\" |References\n|-\n!Primary\n!Secondary\n|-\n|1908\n| ''Les anciennes \u00e9coles de peinture dans les palais et collections priv\u00e9es russes'', by the {{Interlanguage link|Starye gody|lt=''Starye gody''|ru|\u0421\u0442\u0430\u0440\u044b\u0435 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u044b}} magazine\n|[[Imperial Society for the Encouragement of the Arts]], Saint Petersburg\n|286\n|<ref name=\"Benois 1908\" />{{rp|729}}\n| rowspan=\"9\" |{{sfnm|1a1=Grasselli|1a2=Rosenberg|1a3=Parmantier|1y=1984|1p=313|Nemilova|1985|2p=445|Eidelberg|2019}}\n|-\n|1922\u20131925\n|Temporary exhibition of new acqusition from French painting of the 17th and 18th centuries\n|Hermitage Museum, Petrograd (later Leningrad)\n|*\n|<ref name=\"Ersnt\" /><ref name=Miller>{{cite magazine|last=Miller|first=V. F.|title=\u0424\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0446\u0443\u0437\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u0436\u0438\u0432\u043e\u043f\u0438\u0441\u044c XVII-\u0433\u043e \u0438 XVIII-\u0433\u043e \u0432.\u0432. \u0432 \u043d\u043e\u0432\u044b\u0445 \u0437\u0430\u043b\u0430\u0445 \u042d\u0440\u043c\u0438\u0442\u0430\u0436\u0430|work=\u0413\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0434|language=ru|year=1923|issue=1|page=59}}</ref>\n|-\n|1955\n|''An Exhibition of French Art of the 15th-20th Centuries''\n|[[Pushkin Museum]], [[Moscow]]\n|*\n|<ref>{{Cite book|title=\u0412\u044b\u0441\u0442\u0430\u0432\u043a\u0430 \u0444\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0446\u0443\u0437\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0438\u0441\u043a\u0443\u0441\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0430 XV-XX \u0432\u0432. \u041a\u0430\u0442\u0430\u043b\u043e\u0433|last=Antonova|first=I. A.|last2=Berezina|first2=V. N.|last3=Borovaya|first3=T. A.|others=With introduction by {{Interlanguage link|Valeriy Prokofiev|lt=V. Prokofiev|ru|\u041f\u0440\u043e\u043a\u043e\u0444\u044c\u0435\u0432, \u0412\u0430\u043b\u0435\u0440\u0438\u0439 \u041d\u0438\u043a\u043e\u043b\u0430\u0435\u0432\u0438\u0447}}|year=1955|location=Moscow|publisher=Iskusstvo|page=24|language=ru|display-authors=etal|author-link=Irina Antonova}}</ref>\n|-\n|1956\n|''An Exhibition of French Art of the 12th-20th Centuries''\n|Hermitage Museum, Leningrad\n|*\n|<ref>{{Cite book|title=\u0412\u044b\u0441\u0442\u0430\u0432\u043a\u0430 \u0444\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0446\u0443\u0437\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0438\u0441\u043a\u0443\u0441\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0430 XII-XX \u0432\u0432. (1956; \u041b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u043d\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0434). \u041a\u0430\u0442\u0430\u043b\u043e\u0433|last=The Hermitage Museum, Leningrad|publisher=Iskusstvo|year=1956|location=Moscow|page=12|language=ru}}</ref>\n|-\n|1965\n|''Chefs-d'oeuvre de la peinture fran\u00e7aise dans les musees de l'Ermitage et de Moscou''\n|[[Mus\u00e9e des Beaux-Arts de Bordeaux]], [[Bordeaux]]\n|43\n|<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Charensol|first=Georges|date=June 15, 1965|title=Les mus\u00e9es de Russie a Bordeaux|journal=Revue des Deux Mondes|language=fr|pages=607\u2013613|jstor=44590025}}</ref>{{rp|611}}\n|-\n|1965\u20131966\n|''Chefs-d'oeuvre de la peinture fran\u00e7aise dans les musees de l'Ermitage et de Moscou''\n|[[Louvre]], Paris\n|41\n|<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Charensol|first=Georges|date=October 15, 1965|title=L'Ermitage au Louvre|journal=Revue des Deux Mondes|language=fr|pages=610\u2013616|jstor=44591522}}</ref>{{rp|614}}\n|-\n|1972\n|''Watteau and His Time''\n|Hermitage Museum, Leningrad\n|5\n|<ref>{{cite book|title=\u0412\u0430\u0442\u0442\u043e \u0438 \u0435\u0433\u043e \u0432\u0440\u0435\u043c\u044f|author=Hermitage Museum, Leningrad|year=1972|location=Leningrad|publisher=Avrora|pages=12, 21|oclc=990348938}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Cailleux|first=Jean|date=October 1972|title='Watteau and his times' at the Hermitage|journal=[[The Burlington Magazine]]|volume=114|issue=835|pages=733\u2013734|jstor=877114}}</ref>{{rp|734}}\n|-\n|1980\n|''Les arts du th\u00e9\u00e2tre de Watteau \u00e0 Fragonard''\n|Galerie des Beaux-Arts, Mus\u00e9e des Beaux-Arts de Bordeaux, Bordeaux\n|67\n|<ref name=bordeaux1980>{{Cite book|title=Les Arts du th\u00e9\u00e2tre de Watteau \u00e0 Fragonard|publisher=La Galerie|year=1980|location=Bordeaux|page=110|language=fr|oclc=606308317}}</ref>\n|-\n|1984\u20131985\n|''Watteau 1684\u20131721''\n|[[National Gallery of Art]], [[Washington, D.C.]]; [[Galeries nationales du Grand Palais]], Paris; [[Charlottenburg Palace]], [[Berlin]]\n|P. 29\n|<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Opperman|first=Hal|date=June 1988|title=''Watteau 1684-1721'' by Margaret Morgan Grasselli, Pierre Rosenberg and Nicole Parmentier|journal=The Art Bulletin|volume=70|issue=2|pages=354\u2013359|jstor=3051127}}</ref>{{rp|359}}\n|-class=\"sortbottom\"\n|colspan=10 style=font-size:8pt; align=center|\"'''*'''\" denotes an unnumbered entry.\n|}\n\n== Notes ==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n{{refbegin|2|indent=yes}}\n* {{Cite book|title=Watteau; sa vie, son oeuvre.|last=Adhemar|first=Helene|others=Includes \"L\u2019univers de Watteau\", an introduction by [[Ren\u00e9 Huyghe]]|publisher=P. Tisn\u00e9|year=1950|language=fr|location=Paris|oclc=853537|ref=harv|lastauthoramp=y}}\n* {{cite book|last=Belova|first=Y. N.|chapter=\u0410\u0442\u0442\u0440\u0438\u0431\u0443\u0446\u0438\u044f \u0438\u0437\u043e\u0431\u0440\u0430\u0436\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0445 \u043b\u0438\u0446 \u043d\u0430 \u043a\u0430\u0440\u0442\u0438\u043d\u0435 \u0410\u043d\u0442\u0443\u0430\u043d\u0430 \u0412\u0430\u0442\u0442\u043e \"\u0410\u043a\u0442\u0451\u0440\u044b \u0444\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0446\u0443\u0437\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0442\u0435\u0430\u0442\u0440\u0430\" [\"Attribution of persons portrayed by Antoine Watteau in his \"Actors of Theatre French\"]|title=\u042d\u043a\u0441\u043f\u0435\u0440\u0442\u0438\u0437\u0430 \u0438 \u0430\u0442\u0440\u0438\u0431\u0443\u0446\u0438\u044f \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0438\u0437\u0432\u0435\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0439 \u0438\u0437\u043e\u0431\u0440\u0430\u0437\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0438\u0441\u043a\u0443\u0441\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0430: \u043c\u0430\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0438\u0430\u043b\u044b X \u043d\u0430\u0443\u0447\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u043a\u043e\u043d\u0444\u0435\u0440\u0435\u043d\u0446\u0438\u0438|trans-title=Expertise and Attribution of Works of Fine Arts: Materials from the 10th Academic Conference|language=ru|location=Moscow|publisher=Magnum Ars|year=2006|pages=58\u201363|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|editor-first=Ettore|editor-last=Camesasca|url=https://archive.org/details/completepainting0000watt/page/115|url-access=registration|title=The Complete Paintings of Watteau|series=Classics of the World's Great Art|year=1971|location=New York|publisher=Harry N. Abrams|ref=harv|others=Introduction by John Sunderland|isbn=0810955253|page=[https://archive.org/details/completepainting0000watt/page/115 115]|oclc=143069|via=the [[Internet Archive]]}}\n* {{cite book|title=\u0410\u043d\u0442\u0443\u0430\u043d \u0412\u0430\u0442\u0442\u043e|trans-title=Antoine Watteau|language=ru|last=German|first=M. Y.|author-link=Mikhail German|year=2010|origyear=first published in 1980|location=Moscow|publisher=Iskusstvo\u2014XXI vek|isbn=978-5-98051-067-1|ref=harv|oclc=641954308}}\n* {{Cite book|title=Catalogue raisonn\u00e9 de l'oeuvre peint, dessin\u00e9 et grav\u00e9 d'Antoine Watteau|url=https://archive.org/details/catalogueraisonn00gonc_0|last=Goncourt|first=Edmond de|publisher=Rapilly|year=1875|location=Paris|pages=[https://archive.org/details/catalogueraisonn00gonc_0/page/74 74]\u201375|oclc=1041772738|author-link=Edmond de Goncourt|via=the Internet Archive}}\n* {{cite book|last=Grasselli|first=Margaret Morgan|last2=Rosenberg|first2=Pierre|author2-link=Pierre Rosenberg|last3=Parmantier|first3=Nicole|display-authors=etal|title=Watteau, 1684-1721 ; National Gallery of Art, June 17\u2014September 23, 1984; Galeries Nationales du Grand Palais, Paris, October 23, 1984\u2014January 28, 1985; Schloss Charlottenburg, Berlin, February 22\u2014May 26, 1985|publisher=National Gallery of Art|location=Washington|year=1984|ref=harv|via=the National Gallery of Art archive|url=https://www.nga.gov/content/dam/ngaweb/research/publications/pdfs/watteau-1684-1721.pdf|pages=311\u2013313|isbn=0-89468-074-9|oclc=557740787}}{{cbignore}}\n* {{Cite book|title=Antoine Watteau|last=Josz|first=Virgile|year=1904|language=fr|location=Paris|publisher=H. Piazza et cie|via=the Internet Archive|url=https://archive.org/details/gri_33125014989103|oclc=963518006|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|title=Antoine Watteau: catalogue complet de son oeuvre dessin\u00e9|last=Parker|first=Karl T.|author-link=Karl Parker|last2=Mathey|first2=Jacques|lastauthoramp=yes|location=Paris|publisher=F. de Nob\u00e8le|ref=harv|date=1957\u20131958|postscript=. Cat. nos. 53, 64, 84, 541, 729, 823, 828, 914.}}\n* {{cite book|last=Nemilova|first=I. S.|author-link=Inna Nemilova|title=\u0412\u0430\u0442\u0442\u043e \u0438 \u0435\u0433\u043e \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0438\u0437\u0432\u0435\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f \u0432 \u042d\u0440\u043c\u0438\u0442\u0430\u0436\u0435 (Watteau et son \u0153uvre \u00e0 l'Ermitage)|trans-title=Watteau and His Works in the Hermitage|language=ru|publisher=Sovetskiy hudozhnik|location=Leningrad|year=1964|ref=harv|oclc=67871342}}\n* {{cite book|last=Nemilova|first=I. S.|others=Edited by A. S. Kantor-Gukovskaya|title=\u0424\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0446\u0443\u0437\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u0436\u0438\u0432\u043e\u043f\u0438\u0441\u044c. XVIII \u0432\u0435\u043a|trans-title=French Painting: the 18th Century|series=\u0413\u043e\u0441\u0443\u0434\u0430\u0440\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u042d\u0440\u043c\u0438\u0442\u0430\u0436. \u0421\u043e\u0431\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u0437\u0430\u043f\u0430\u0434\u043d\u043e\u0435\u0432\u0440\u043e\u043f\u0435\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u0436\u0438\u0432\u043e\u043f\u0438\u0441\u0438: \u043d\u0430\u0443\u0447\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u043a\u0430\u0442\u0430\u043b\u043e\u0433 \u0432 16 \u0442\u043e\u043c\u0430\u0445|volume=10|date=1985|location=Leningrad|publisher=Iskusstvo|pages=444\u2013445|ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book|title=\u0417\u0430\u0433\u0430\u0434\u043a\u0438 \u0441\u0442\u0430\u0440\u044b\u0445 \u043a\u0430\u0440\u0442\u0438\u043d|last=Nemilova|first=I. S.|publisher=Izobrazitel'noe iskusstvo|year=1989|origyear=first published in 1973|isbn=5-85200-017-5|oclc=909190011|edition=3rd|location=Moscow|language=ru|trans-title=Enigmas of Old Masters|re